  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Prayer for Clear Skies
  author: Jung Po
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The great fields bear abundant grain, awaiting autumn's ripening promise.
    Yet three days of downpour descend—
    I fear the crops may suffer harm.

    With earnest heart I pour forth this plea,
    daring to seek the merciful grace
    of Heaven's benevolent care for the humble folk below.

    Heaven's brightness follows the people's desire—
    I beseech you: disperse the clouds and shadow,
    clear the gloom in a single moment.
    Let the year bring forth abundance and prosperity,
    and may joyous voices rise like boiling waters
    from all the lands near and far.
  footnotes:
    - This is a prayer-blessing (祝文) presented to Heaven during a rain ceremony, requesting clear skies to protect ripening crops from excessive moisture damage.
    - The phrase 'three days' (三日) refers to a continuous period of heavy rain during the critical growing season.
    - The imagery of 'boiling waters' (沸) for celebration suggests an intensity of joy and communal festivity throughout the realm.
